<div id="review_3461375205" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3461375205" />
    <a title="Eugenea Pollock" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38458766-eugenea-pollock"><img alt="Eugenea Pollock" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3461375205?book_show_action=true">Jul 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eugenea Pollock" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eugenea Pollock" href="/user/show/38458766-eugenea-pollock">Eugenea Pollock</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38458766-eugenea-pollock?shelf=bookbub-buys">bookbub-buys</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/38458766-eugenea-pollock?shelf=short-story-collections">short-story-collections</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3461375205" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13126772818690136176">Short stories have their own particular appeal, and I have long been under their spell, whether they spring from the pen of Nobelist Alice Munro, Anton Chekhov, Amy Hempel, Tracy Chevalier, or, as here, Isabel Allende. This collection, however, is one of the most poetic in style that I have read— just BEAUTIFULLY written. The settings are wide-ranging and intriguing: frontier justice in “A Schoolteacher’s Guest”, harrowing rescue efforts after a volcanic eruption in “And of Clay Are We Created”,</span>
  <span id="freeText13126772818690136176" style="display:none">Short stories have their own particular appeal, and I have long been under their spell, whether they spring from the pen of Nobelist Alice Munro, Anton Chekhov, Amy Hempel, Tracy Chevalier, or, as here, Isabel Allende. This collection, however, is one of the most poetic in style that I have read— just BEAUTIFULLY written. The settings are wide-ranging and intriguing: frontier justice in “A Schoolteacher’s Guest”, harrowing rescue efforts after a volcanic eruption in “And of Clay Are We Created”, a magical fairy tale reminiscent of a modern-day Green Mansions in “Phantom Palace”, fulfillment of an ironic prediction in “The Judge’s Wife”, and about twenty more. I highly recommend this book whether you are already fond of the genre or not. Try it out—you will not be sorry!</span>
  <a data-text-id="13126772818690136176" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


